Their opinions were mostly influenced by the centrality of motherhood which influences the process of socialization in Cyprus. The character of abortion legislation has therefore decided not only social norms, values and culture but also political forces as a result of the great political consistence between Chrysi Avgi and the Church in the context of Cyprus, which have not yet disappeared from the public life of the island (Kofinas 1985, 152–4). The Turkish governmental and political forces that were introduced into the Cyprus issue after 1974 (see Luleci 2013; Oskan 2014) created further ambiguity. Turkey, on one side asked the Cypriot church to protect and promote the Ottoman culture in Cyprus, but on the other, supported Turkey’s secular nature. According to this ambiguous ‘double faced’ cultural orientation of Turkey, people were confused and by this Turkish forces’ implementation of their secular interest on the island, left a lot of chinks for the Church, which could exploit social gaps, and have strong influence on the urban population (Bakis 2009, 413). Specifically this was distinctive in Northern Cyprus. The collaboration between secular and religious groups was one of an informal alliance based on common views and objectives (Kalfayan 2007, 155) and this alliance was able to dominate every political aspect
